{{good article}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}
{{DISPLAYTITLE:Controversies surrounding ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2''}}
''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]'' is a [[first-person shooter]] video game developed by [[Infinity Ward]] and published by [[Activision]]. Released worldwide on November 10, 2009, it generated several controversies. In the game's fourth [[level (video gaming)|level]], "[[No Russian]]", the player controls an undercover [[CIA]] agent who participates in a [[mass shooting]] at a [[Moscow]] airport to gain the trust of a Russian [[terrorist]] group. This level was largely criticized for allowing players to partake in a terrorist attack, and international versions of the game were subject to censorship due to the level's content. Allegations of [[Homophobia|homophobic]] content arose when Infinity Ward released a video titled "Fight Against Grenade Spam". Some video game journalists chastised the video's use of [[profanity]], and that the video's title forms the [[acronym]] [[faggot (slang)|F.A.G.S.]], a pejorative for gay people. In response, Infinity Ward removed the video from [[YouTube]]. An [[easter egg (media)|easter egg]] referencing the United States policy "[[don't ask, don't tell]]" was also seen as homophobic, though most journalists belittled these allegations. The [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] version of the game was also met with criticism from players, when it was revealed that the game would not support dedicated [[game server|servers]] among a litany of other changes. Windows players created an [[online petition]] to allow for dedicated servers, receiving over 150,000 signatures in ten days. However, despite these controversies, ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2'' grossed [[United States dollar|$]]310 million in its first day of release.

=="No Russian"==
{{main article|No Russian}}
[[File:NoRussian.jpg|right|thumb|256px|In "No Russian", the player can shoot at a group of civilians at an airport.]]
In the game's fourth [[level (video gaming)|level]], "No Russian", the player controls an undercover [[CIA]] agent who participates in a [[mass shooting]] at a [[Moscow]] airport to gain the trust of a Russian [[terrorist]] group.<ref name="After 911"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Yin-Poole|first=Wesley|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-03-15-call-of-duty-no-russian-actors-tearful|title=Call of Duty No Russian actors "tearful"|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 15, 2011|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> It begins with the player walking out of an elevator with four other gunmen, who proceed to open fire on a large group of civilians at a [[airport security|security checkpoint]].<ref name="After 911">{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Matthew|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phj-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA80&lpg=PA80&dq=closing+the+perspectival+distance+in+%22no+russian%22&source=bl&ots=eg4rbjJI8W&sig=ooiIRfjqF2Q2CP99uO1TKj9wjQw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik1d-dzJzOAhUTwWMKHReGD4gQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=closing%20the%20perspectival%20distance%20in%20%22no%20russian%22&f=false|title=Playing War: Military Video Games After 9/11|chapter=The First-Personal Shooter|publisher=[[New York University Press]]|date=April 2016|p=80}}</ref> The player then accompanies the gunmen as they walk through the airport, killing any remaining civilians. The only legitimate targets are a group of security personnel encountered in waves throughout the airport interior, and a more heavily armed gang of riot squad members deployed on the tarmac. The level is very graphic, as screams can be heard throughout, and the injured crawl away leaving blood trails.<ref name="Artful">{{cite web|last=Peckham|first=Matt|authorlink=Matt Peckham|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/181140/modern_warfare_2_artful.html|title=Is Call of Duty Modern Warfare 2 Terrorist Gameplay Artful?|work=[[PC World]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> However, the player is never forced to partake in the massacre, and may instead let their comrades kill the civilians. If the player does not feel comfortable during the level, they are allowed to skip to the next level with no penalties.<ref name="That Time">{{cite web|last=Klepek|first=Patrick|url=http://kotaku.com/that-time-call-of-duty-let-you-shoot-up-an-airport-1738376241|title=
That Time ''Call of Duty'' Let You Shoot Up An Airport|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=October 23, 2015|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

Prior to the release of ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2'', footage taken from the "No Russian" level was leaked on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thorsen|first=Tor|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/modern-warfare-2-massacre-not-representative-of-overall-experience-activision/1100-6238331/|title=Modern Warfare 2 massacre 'not representative of overall experience' - Activision|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Though some journalists were cautious towards the level's content, they decided to wait until they could actually play the level to judge its merits.<ref name="Artful"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Hoggins|first=Tom|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/6460444/Call-Of-Duty-Modern-Warfare-2-leaked-footage-analysis.html|title=Call Of Duty: Modern Warfare 2 leaked footage analysis|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wildgoose|first=David|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2009/11/monday-musings-war-games/|title=Monday Musings: War Games|work=[[Kotaku|Kotaku Australia]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> After the game's release, "No Russian" was largely criticized for allowing players to partake in a terrorist attack. Vince Horiuchi of ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]'' felt that the level was in poor taste following the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]], and questioned why the level couldn't have been told through a non-interactive [[cutscene]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Horiuchi|first=Vince|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/technology/ci_13799461|title=Oh My Tech: 'Call of Duty' has troubling scene|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=November 16, 2009|accessdate=December 12, 2009}}</ref> Marc Cieslak of [[BBC News]] was saddened by "No Russian", as he felt it disproved his theory that the [[video game industry]] had "grown up".<ref>{{cite web|last=Orry|first=James|url=http://www.videogamer.com/xbox360/cod_modern_warfare_2/news/bbc_reporter_saddened_but_not_shocked_by_mw2.html|title=BBC reporter 'saddened' but not 'shocked' by MW2|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=November 10, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Several prominent British religious leaders condemned "No Russian": [[Alexander Goldberg]] of the [[London Jewish Forum]] was worried that children would play the level; Fazan Mohammed of the [[British Muslim Forum]] described the level as an intimate experience of enacting terrorism; and [[Stephen Lowe (bishop of Hulme)|Stephen Lowe]], the retired [[Bishop of Hulme]], felt that the level was "sickening".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ingham|first=Tim|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/religious-leaders-slam-modern-warfare-2|title=Religious leaders slam Modern Warfare 2|work=[[The Market for Computer & Video Games]]|date=November 16, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Due to the graphic content featured in "No Russian", ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2'' was subject to censorship in international versions of the game, including the entire removal of the level from the Russian version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Welsh|first=Oli|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/activision-chose-to-censor-russian-mw2|title=Activision chose to censor Russian MW2|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 17, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|url=http://kotaku.com/5422287/modern-warfare-2-censored-in-japan|title=Modern Warfare 2 Censored In Japan|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=December 9, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

==Allegations of homophobic content==
In October 2009, Infinity Ward posted a video titled "Fight Against Grenade Spam" on [[YouTube]]. In the video, professional baseball player [[Cole Hamels]] delivers a [[public service announcement]] that advocates against the use of grenade [[Spam (gaming)|spam]]. Hamels uses [[profanity]] in the video, calling grenade spam "for [[pussy#weakness|pussies]]", and says "what the fuck" when he is blown up with grenades.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarkar|first=Samit|url=https://www.destructoid.com/cole-hamels-pussies-use-random-mw2-grenades-update--153686.phtml|title=Cole Hamels: 'Pussies' use random MW2 grenades (Update)|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Kotaku 1">{{cite web|last=Good|first=Owen|url=http://kotaku.com/5394032/cole-hamels-reminds-you-that-grenades-are-for-pussies|title=Cole Hamels Reminds You That Grenades are "for Pussies"|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=October 30, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> Soon after the video was released, it was quickly discovered that the video's title forms the [[acronym]] [[faggot (slang)|F.A.G.S.]], which is a pejorative term against [[gay]] people.<ref name="Gamasutra">{{cite web|last=Graft|first=Kris|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/116843/Infinity_Ward_Pulls_Modern_Warfare_2_Video_Amid_Criticism.php|title=Infinity Ward Pulls ''Modern Warfare 2'' Video Amid Criticism|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> Phillip Kollar of ''[[Game Informer]]'' criticized that the title's acronym and use of profanity, and felt that Infinity Ward was condoning homophobic slurs.<ref name="Kotaku 2">{{cite web|last=Good|first=Owen|url=http://kotaku.com/5394595/infinity-ward-removes-modern-warfare-2-fags-video|title=Infinity Ward Removes Modern Warfare 2 "F.A.G.S." Video|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=November 1, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Freelance]] journalist Mitchell Dyer echoed Kollar's statement, and commented that the video "seems to enforce the asshole-ry" of homophobic slurs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sarkar|first=Samit|url=https://www.destructoid.com/infinity-ward-pulls-mw2-hamels-video-after-internet-furor-153731.phtml|title=Infinity Ward pulls MW2 Hamels video after Internet furor|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=October 31, 2016|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> In response to the backlash, Infinity Ward community manager Robert Bowling remarked that while the video was intended to be a [[social commentary]] joke, he understood why people found it offensive, and removed the video from YouTube.<ref name="Gamasutra"/>

Further allegations of homophobic content arose when a [[Easter egg (media)|easter egg]] was discovered in the game's opening [[tutorial]] level. If the player remains idle for a brief period of time, they are able to hear one soldier ask another soldier about his sexuality, and then remark "don't ask, don't tell".<ref name="Destructoid Easter Egg">{{cite web|last=Sterling|first=Jim|authorlink=Jim Sterling|url=https://www.destructoid.com/modern-warfare-2-has-a-homophobic-easter-egg--156677.phtml|title=Modern Warfare 2 has a homophobic Easter egg!?|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=December 2, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name="The Register Easter Egg">{{cite web|last=Sherwood|first=James|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/12/09/mw2_gay/|title=''Modern Warfare 2'' hit by anti-gay claim|work=[[The Register]]|date=December 9, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> This easter egg references the United States policy "[[Don't ask, don't tell]]", which prevented openly gay people from serving in the [[United States Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bumiller|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/us/23military.html|title=Obama Ends 'Don't Ask, Don't Tell' Policy|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 22, 2011|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> Unlike the "Fight Against Grenade Spam" video, few journalists commented on the easter egg. [[Jim Sterling]] of ''[[Destructoid]]'' felt that the easter egg was "too silly/stupid" for him to be angry at,<ref name="Destructoid Easter Egg"/> while James Sherwood of ''[[The Register]]'' commented that people were trying to generate controversy over unimportant dialogue.<ref name="The Register Easter Egg"/> Lyle Masaki of [[Logo TV]]'s NewNowNext.com deemed the easter egg to be homophobic, but not representative of the game as a whole.<ref>{{cite web|last=Masaki|first=Lyle|url=http://www.newnownext.com/what-does-a-homophobic-joke-tell-us-about-call-of-duty-modern-warfare-2/12/2009/|title=What does a homophobic joke tell us about "Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2"?|publisher=[[Logo TV|NewNowNext.com]]|date=December 9, 2009|accessdate=August 4, 2016}}</ref>

==Criticism of the Windows version==
In a [[webcast]] conducted prior to the game's release, Bowling revealed that the [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] version of ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2'' would not support dedicated [[Game server|servers]], and would instead be powered by the IWNet server.<ref>{{cite web|last=Robinson|first=Martin|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/10/19/no-dedicated-servers-for-pc-mw2|title=No Dedicated Servers For PC MW2|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=October 19, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> Infinity Ward would go on to state that the Windows version would also lack [[Command (computing)|console commands]], not support [[multiplayer]] matches larger than 18 players, and the inability for players to ban other players who are [[Cheating in online games|cheating]].<ref name="arstechnica1">{{cite web|last=Kuchera|first=Ben|authorlink=Ben Kuchera|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2009/11/pc-modern-warfare-2-its-much-worse-than-you-thought/|title=PC Modern Warfare 2: it's much worse than you thought|work=[[Ars Technica]]|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=November 15, 2009}}</ref> These decisions angered many Windows gamers, with Ben Kuchera of ''[[Ars Technica]]'' commenting: "at launch, this will be one of the most locked-down, inflexible, and gamer-unfriendly game ever created."<ref name="arstechnica1"/> An [[online petition]] was created to have Infinity Ward allow dedicated servers, which surpassed 150,000 signatures in ten days.<ref name="Ars Technica">{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Michael|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2009/10/modern-warfare-2-the-case-for-the-dedicated-server/|title=Modern Warfare 2: the case for the dedicated server|work=[[Ars Technica]]|date=October 29, 2016|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, users on [[Amazon.com]] submitted over 125 one-star reviews for the Windows version of the game.<ref name="1UP">{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Chris|url=http://www.1up.com/news/gamers-hate-modern-warfare-2|title=Why Do PC Gamers Hate Modern Warfare 2's New Matchmaking System?|work=[[1UP.com]]|date=October 21, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609144750/http://www.1up.com/news/gamers-hate-modern-warfare-2|archivedate=June 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mike Griffiths, [[CEO]] of Activision, stated that while Infinity Ward was aware of the petition, they weren't overly worried. He commented that IWNet would allow for a "friendly consumer experience", and that the benefits outweighed the negatives.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Matt|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/activision-not-overly-concerned-by-modern-warfare-2-pc-complaints|title=Activision "not overly concerned" by MW2 PC complaints|publisher=Gameindustry.biz|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> ''Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2'' would go on to sell more than 4.7 million copies and gross [[United States dollar|$]]310 million in the United States and United Kingdom in its first day of release.<ref>{{cite web|last=Orry|first=James|url=http://www.videogamer.com/xbox360/cod_modern_warfare_2/news/modern_warfare_2_sells_4_7_million_day_one_in_us_and_uk.html|title=Modern Warfare 2 sells 4.7 million day one in US and UK|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=November 12, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> According to Bowling, while only 3% of the game's sales came from the Windows version, it still outsold the Windows version of ''[[Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare]]'' in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|url=http://kotaku.com/5409738/modern-warfare-2-selling-just-fine-on-pc|title=Modern Warfare 2 Selling Just Fine On PC|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=November 11, 2009|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref>

